snippet.textDisplay:
Terminator is all about changing the future and alternate timelines. Anything after T2 I consider an alternate timeline(s) because Sarah and John saved their timeline in the director's cut of T2. They prevented Judgement Day and it shows an elderly Sarah sitting at a park talking about a future that never was, with John in his 50's pushing his daughter/Sarah's granddaughter on a swing. Sarah says John ended up becoming a senator. Now that just proves that no matter what happened, John grew up to become a great leader.

I don't think of it as the other movies not happening, I think of it as a different timeline branching out after T2; a timeline where John and Sarah failed to save their timeline. Yes John dies in the first 2 minutes, but it's not OUR John. OUR John saved his timeline and lived happily ever after in the director's cut ending of T2. All of the other movies still happened, just not in this timeline. Emilia Clarke is a young Sarah in T5, but it's not the same Sarah from OUR timeline. We don't talk about the movie, but remember that Sarah was dead in T3? But that wasn't OUR Sarah.

I went into the movie knowing that John died, but I kept the mindset as explained above and it let me look past that death quite easily. Maybe it's because I read a lot of comics where alternate timelines and parallel/alternate Earths have been a thing for a long, long time. Yes I was a bit bummed when Spider-Man died, but that was just one of many Spideys in the multiverse so it was okay.
With this mindset, I was able to enjoy the movie

snippet.textDisplay: This video honestly makes me so glad I didn't bother seeing this movie. Also, was I the only one who loved Genysis? I thought it was one of the smarter and more logically consistent time-travel films of the past decade or so. Part of me not seeing Dark Fate was an angry protest that Dark Fate got made instead of a Genysis sequel (which almost assuredly would've done gangbusters in China, if not the US, and likely would've been more successful than DF).
